commText: Mumbai Indians chased down 200-plus targets for fun at the Wankhede, and they were on the course to do the same tonight after the kind of start Kishan and Rohit got them off to. However, the Giants didn't lose hope against the five-time IPL champions. LSG are most likely to make it to the playoffs after this win. But you never know in the IPL! If Mumbai Indians win their next game, and Punjab Kings/Royal Challengers win their remaining two games, and LSG lose against KKR, they can still miss out on a chance to book a berth in the playoffs. Plenty of permutations and combinations going into the final week of the league stage. We'll make sure to bring all the action. For now, it's a goodbye from our side! See you tomorrow!

commText: B0$ I was having cramps, I pulled a muscle. I have always been a team player, anything for the team, so happy with the result. Mohsin has a big heart. He had a surgery and playing IPL after such a thing, then sky is the limit. It has not been easy for us, really happy to end on a good note here. Good to give them a win in this last game at this venue.

B0$ The plan was to execute what I did in practice and I executed. Even Krunal was talking to me and I told him the same. The run-up is the same, did not change it in the last over. I was trying to calm myself down, not look at the scoreboard and bowl the 6 balls well. Since the wicket was gripping, I tried the slower ball, but I bowled two of those and then changed to the yorker and it was reversing as well. Been a tough time as I was injured, playing after a year. My father got discharged from the ICU yesterday and he was in the hospital for the last 10 days and I did it for him, he would have been watching. I'm grateful to the team and the support staff, Gautam [Gambhir] sir, Vijay [Dahiya] sir for playing me this game even though I did not do well last game.

B0$ We didn't play well enough to win the game. There were little moments in the game that we didn't win unfortunately. We gave too many runs at the back end and the last three overs went for a few. But the way we started with the bat we were in a good position to chase, but like I said we lost our way in the second half. He (Stoinis) played really well, kept hitting straight which is what you need to do on a pitch like this. It was a brilliant knock from him. Not sure how the calculation (about the points and NRR) will work, but we need to come out and play some good cricket in our last game (against SRH).

B0$ Quite an exhilarating victory for the Super Giants! They have managed to down the five-time IPL champions! MI's openers got them off to a rollicking start in the run chase, but didn't the LSG bowlers pull things back in emphatic style? Rohit and Kishan added 90 runs for the opening wicket, but once Rohit departed, the momentum got back in LSG's favour. Kishan notched up a scintillating fifty, however, once he was dismissed, LSG grabbed back the momentum even further. SKY and Wadhera failed to get going, and although Tim David hit a few lusty blows, Lucknow's death bowling was impressive enough to strangle them eventually. Quite clearly one of the best pitches to bat on, at this particular venue, and it was none other than Marcus Stoinis who made the difference. Failed to get going at this venue earlier in the tournament did Stoinis, but there's always a first time. Tonight was his night, and didn't he play like a warrior to take LSG to 15 points. With this win, he has helped the Giants inch closer to sealing a spot in the playoffs. Stay around for the presentations folks!

In the face of more than a month of winless run at home, Lucknow Super Giants 'Adab Se Harayenge' campaign is proving slightly counter-productive, possibly even stretching its nawabi warmth a little too much for their own comfort. And as they prepare to strengthen their campaign in its most sensitive phase, they are coming up against a rampant Mumbai Indians team. 
 
On the face of it, there seems a lot out of place for the visitors. 
 
Jasprit Bumrah and Jofra Archer have been ruled out with their respective injuries. And there is no close substitute for them in world cricket, let alone the squad that MI has assembled. 
 
 
Rohit Sharma has struggled for form, now for several seasons running. 
 
Two promising and destructive South African batters - Dewald Brevis and Tristan Stubbs, honed last season for the challenges of IPL, are just not getting ample opportunities. 
 
Tilak Verma, their last season's find, remains uncertain. 
 
And yet, somehow, despite a slow start in the season, Mumbai Indians find themselves in with a chance of finishing in the top two. 
 
It's a tricky phase for both the teams right now, and Piyush Chawla has already sounded a warning of not getting carried away with this timely momentum crossing that thin line that separates confidence from overconfidence for Mumbai Indians. 
 
Much of MI's recent success has come at the back of their batting muscle that has plundered big runs and chased down 200-plus scores too easily for the comfort of the opposition teams. In Lucknow, the challenges would be different. 
 
From the flat and fast tracks, they would have to adjust their game to the slow turners. They struggled in Chennai recently, and it's only going to get more complicated in LSG's home turf - which has been the lowest scoring venue by far this season. 
 
If history counts for anything, they are yet to beat LSG in IPL. However, there are two points to salvage for the visitors. The last two times they were defeated, KL Rahul had scored centuries. He won't be around this time. Secondly, despite a plethora of spin options and good players of spin, LSG themselves haven't figured out the blueprint for sustained success - at the venue and in the tournament.
